cs.SI, cs.CL, cs.SOC, cs.LG, cs.IR 

The paper deals with analyzing influences on users in social media, which involves natural language processing, network analysis, and machine learning. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), followed by cs.CL (Computation and Language) as the paper proposes a new non-parametric model for analyzing social media data. The paper also involves machine learning techniques for designing inference algorithms, which makes cs.LG (Machine Learning) a likely sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with topic trends and user personality trends, which could fall under cs.IR (Information Retrieval). Finally, the paper involves analyzing large-scale social media data, which could also fall under cs.SOC (Computers and Society).
